Date: 0/0/1956
Source: NZ Fishes: An Identification Guide
Author: GRAHAM
Vol / Page: 121
Edition:
Quote: SILVERSIDE or SNODGALL <i>Argentina elongata</i> Hutton. Although Silverside is the correct name, almost all fishermen continue to call this fish Snodgall but none has been able to tell me how the name originated. The name Silverside is derived from its glistening, silvery body, ...
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1981
Source: Fisherman's Bible
Author: WILSON
Vol / Page: 243
Edition:
Quote: SILVERSIDE A rare inhabitant of our southern waters of yesteryear. Looking like a / large, big-eyed sprat this fish was once common around Dunedin where it was highly-prized for food and even, at one stage of the subject a canning industry. ... Completely toothless it was also known as the Snodgall, not to be confused however with Snodgall's Trevalla of which it is no relation. Appears to have largely vanished.
Notes:

